        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9005.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from T. H. Farrer, 12 August 1873</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9003.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to T. H. Farrer, 10 August [1873]</ref> and n. 2. Farrer described these observations on <hi rend="italic">Coronilla varia</hi> (purple crown vetch; now <hi rend="italic">Securigera varia</hi>) in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2464.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Farrer 1874</ref>, p. 169.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Inflorescences of <hi rend="italic">Coronilla</hi> are umbels composed of several individual flowers (five to twenty in the case of <hi rend="italic">C. varia</hi>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Farrer probably refers to <hi rend="italic">Bombus lapidarius</hi>, the red-tailed humble-bee or bumble-bee.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9005.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from T. H. Farrer, 12 August 1873</ref>. Farrer refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_6500.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">George Payne</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5019.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Hensleigh Wedgwood</ref> was the author of a <hi rend="italic">Dictionary of English etymology</hi>, a second edition of which was published in 1872 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8252.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">H. Wedgwood 1872</ref>).</note>
